description:
lichen_util.h:60-90 negates err, then switches on the positive value. The 'Make err positive' comment is misleading since err itself is not modified.

What goes wrong: Future maintainers may add cases with wrong sign, causing silent fall-through to 'unknown error'.

Rewrite:
```c
static inline const char *lichen_link_strerror(int err)
{
    if (err >= 0) {
        return "success";
    }
    switch (err) {
    case -EINVAL:
        return "invalid argument";
    case -ENOMEM:
        return "buffer too small";
    case -EMSGSIZE:
        return "frame too large";
#ifdef EOVERFLOW
    case -EOVERFLOW:
        return "nonce exhausted";
#endif
#ifdef EALREADY
    case -EALREADY:
        return "replay detected";
#endif
#if HAVE_LICHEN_ERRNO
    case -LICHEN_EAUTH:
        return "authentication failed";
#endif
    default:
        return "unknown error";
    }
}
```

This is simpler, the cases match the actual values passed, and there's no mental translation required.
